Hi Mark,

This did used to be possible, but unfortunately it got broken when I added some checks about overwriting objects in the list, and the `kwarg` add functions.

In https://github.com/robshakir/pyangbind/commit/0c28c057eeb7034c23c94a4e7ec09a9fd2ae00d0 (rather a hefty commit, since it's on my working branch) then these functions are restored as I'd noted this as part of a wider set of usability fixes that I'm adding based on an internal implementation.

Essentially, if we have a module:

```
module pond {
    namespace "http://rob.sh/pond";
    prefix "pond"; 

    list fish {
        key "type";

        leaf type {
            type string;
        }
        
        leaf number-in-pond {
            type uint64;
        }
    }
}
```

Then with bindings generated from the `docs` branch, then the following is now possible:

```python
#!/usr/bin/env python

from ybind import pond
from ybind.fish import fish

p = pond()

f = fish()
f.type = "salmon"
f.number_in_pond = 42

p.fish.add(type=f.type, _v=f)

print p.get(filter=True)

p.fish.add(type="koi")
passed = False
try:
    p.fish["koi"].type = "walrus"
except AttributeError:
    passed = True

assert passed is True, "Should not be able to modify a list item key value"

p.fish._item(type="koi").number_in_pond = 99

print p.get(filter=True)
```

This will output:

```
[~/Code/pyangbind/tmp(docs*)]
(17:19 - s001) latte> python pondtest.py
{'fish': {u'salmon': {'type': u'salmon', 'number-in-pond': 42}}}
{'fish': {'koi': {'type': u'koi', 'number-in-pond': 99}, u'salmon': {'type': u'salmon', 'number-in-pond': 42}}}
```

HTH,
r.

@madig If all you need is stability (i.e. once you have something working, you don't want us to automatically upgrade underneath you and break everything) then it is as simple as checking out the same commit from our upstream vcpkg repository. Each commit has hashes for all downstream libraries, so you're guaranteed to get exactly the same results every time, as long as you keep pulling the same tarball (for example: https://github.com/Microsoft/vcpkg/archive/a477fd6b6eb5a4053770e50423c6f1144c338c4d.zip).

If forking sounds harder than having a few files you replace after extracting, that's fine too! We build whatever is in the `ports\` directory when you run `vcpkg install`, so you can alter those freely.

The harfbuzz-freetype situation is quite challenging for every package manager it seems (which is why we haven't tackled it). My gut says that the practical way to solve it is to merge the two into a single "harfbuzz-freetype" build which internally does the loop. You could replace our existing `harfbuzz` and `freetype` ports with dummy forwarders to the combo-build, and all the other scripts should just work :).

