        myFunc(myPet);

FYI: note that you can already wrap vectors as numpy arrays *without* copying, kind of like so:

```cpp
struct Data {
    std::vector<int> vec;
};

py::class_<Data>(m, "Data")
    .def("vec", [](Data& self) -> py::array {  // no copying
        return {self.vec.data(), self.vec.size(), py::cast(self);
    });
```

Untested, but something like this should work.

@FrancescAlted btw I think you can just use `.data()` here without having to request a buffer, i.e.

```cpp
auto xptr = xbuf.data();
auto rptr = rbuf.mutable_data();
```

